Description: reality mode marker (suffixed to subject pronoun)
Name: *-a, -Ta

Description: alienable object (with possessive suffix), acquire an alienable object
Name: *aa-, aa-ni-
*afaŋi
Comment: _Cf._ [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _epaŋ_ glossed as ‘south’ in dictionary looks like a loan (_p_ unexpected, see [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*aúrú_ ‘south’). _Cf._ [Marck’s (1994:310/323)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*faŋi_ ‘dry season’.

Name: *afara
Comment: There appears to have been corruption of the word for ‘shoulder carrying pole’ and its reinterpretation as ‘shoulder’ in [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), and [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian).

Description: carry on the hip or under the arm
Name: *afi, afi-Si-
*-aki
Comment: Reflexes of this suffix that have been recorded for [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) (see examples under [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-aki-ni](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-passivesuffix-2) below) all have it followed by reflexes of _*-ni_. See the statement about [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _-ási_ (_-esi_) in [Goodenough and Sugita 1980](Source#cldf:goodenoughandsugita1980).

Name: *alele
Comment: There is no basis for relating [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _anene_ to [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*taReRe_ ‘rejoice’, as suggested by [Geraghty (1990)](Source#cldf:geraghty1990). _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) ? _*kaúlú_ ‘sing, song’ and [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*alle_ ‘count, enumerate’. There may be two different roots here.

Name: *-ali, -aliali, mʷa-aliali
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*ka-falli_ ‘be careful of, attend to’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*mʷaali_ ‘confused, mistaken’.

Name: *al[iu]ta
Comment: Note [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) _d_ instead of expected _t_, there may be a problem here.

Name: *alo
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _yaal’_ ‘sun’ is probably a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian). See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*yalle-pʷuta_ ‘a tree (_Pittosporum_)’ and cf. [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*yaado_ ‘legendary woman’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*a⎣sS⎦o](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-time-1) ‘time’.

Name: *alo, aloalo, alo-[fØ]i
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) form appears to be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *amʷii
Comment: Could be loans in [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese).

Description: to have or take in hand, to handle
Name: *aŋa₁
*apara
Comment: Note that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) seems to have reinterpreted this form as having a causative prefix and derived the secondary forms marked # accordingly. The [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms cannot be understood as having a causative prefix.

Name: *are, are-ki
Comment: The following forms would indicate a low stem vowel instead, as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ara:_.

Name: *ari
Comment: Rounding in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms unexplained; possible contamination by reflexes of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _aru_, which are now near homonyms with [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) reflexes cited here. Semantics of [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) form help explain possible confusion between these two etyma, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ari_ and _*aru_.

Name: *aru, aruaru, aru-ti-
Comment: Note that the initial _g_ of the [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _garusu_ is unexpected, unless the form is a misrendering of _*(ga)-aru-su_ with a causative prefix.

Name: *atu
Comment: The _*l_ of the [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) reconstruction depends entirely on the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) forms, which may result from loans.

Name: *au-
Comment: This does not seem to be cognate with [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*[qØ]aRu_ ‘dew’ [Geraghty 1990](Source#cldf:geraghty1990). See also Loans: [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _éwú-ni-yár_.

Name: *[ao]ut[ae]
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _(te)-kouti_ ‘small mat worn over the shoulders’ appears to be loan from English coat

Description: 1st plural inclusive possessive pronoun, of us, our
Name: *-ca
*ca-
Comment: _Cf._ [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _tεtε-_ or _tεtε-n_ in such honorific expressions as _tεtεmpala_, _tεtεnsik_. See [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*cafifi](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-twistedtangled-1) ‘twisted, tangled’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*ca-riwariwa_ ‘be shiny, glossy, bright, glitter’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*cééú_ ‘continuously widespread’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*cappa_ ‘be turned face down’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*coroŋo_ ‘noisy condition’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*caapaapa_ ‘flattened’.

Name: *cakai
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form also reflects [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*sakau_ ‘reef’, the two reflexes apparently having become homonyms closely similar in meaning, as noted by [Marck (1994:317)](Source#cldf:marck1994), who reconstructs this as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*t’akau_.

Name: *canu-, cacanu, canucanu
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:309)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*t’anu_ fresh water, nonsaline flowing liquids in general.

Name: *cece, cecece
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*cee, ceecee_ ‘move quickly’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*cici](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tremble-1) ‘tremble’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*rere](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tremblewithfear-1) ‘tremble (with fear)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*caka-i-, ccaka-i-_ ‘chase, pursue’.

Name: *ceni, ceceni
Comment: Note that the vowel _e_ in the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form is unexpected (we expect _i_). [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _cheen_ ‘a beach heliotrope’ appears to be a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *ciilee
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _cili (?)_‘have a sty in the eye.

Description: have a sty in the eye
Name: *cili
Comment: There seems to be a problem with the vowel of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ciilee ?_ (?) ‘swelling’.

Description: tip up, raise up, nod, bob
Name: *cimʷe
*cipʷa₁
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*cipʷa₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tongs-1) ‘tongs’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _kupʷe-li kupʷe,_ ‘be bent, to bend (something).

Name: *cipʷa₂
Comment: Reference may originally have been to a green stick that was bent (broken) to make tongs. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*cipʷa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-curvebendinward-1) ‘curve, bend inward’.

Name: *cuu, cuu-ŋi
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _su-n_ ‘to meet (someone), arrive at (a place)’ is presumably a loan.

Name: *cuyi-
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*cúyicúyi_ ‘yard, boom (of canoe)’. Note that this example, along with [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _mʷotu-Si mʷotu,_ ‘cut, sever, break off’, shows that pre [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) _*ns_ merged with [Pre-Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:preprotooceanic) _*nd_ and _*nt_ as [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) _*d_, contrary to present reconstructions for [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) ([Grace 1969](Source#cldf:grace1969), [Ross 1988](Source#cldf:ross1988)). For further discussion and examples, see [Goodenough 1992 fn. 6](Source#cldf:goodenough1992), [Goodenough 1997](Source#cldf:goodenough1997).

Description: lee platform of sailing canoe, platform on side opposite to outrigger float
Name: *epaepa
*etieti
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*[kØ]aTe-i-, [kØ]aTTe-i-_ ‘tear or peel with the teeth’.

Name: *fa-
Comment: Note [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _sefáŋŋ_, _sefáŋ_ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _hefáŋ_ are metathasized forms of _fe sáŋŋ_ and *_fe háng_ respectively.

Name: *faa-
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _faa-[sS]i faa,_ ‘apply the sole of the foot’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*fa[ae]fa[ae]_ ‘footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*faa-raki_ ‘use one's foot’.

Name: *faa-, fa-
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*faŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-thenumberfourinserialcounting-1) ‘the number four’ (in serial counting).

Description: apply the sole of the foot
Name: *faa, faa-[sS]i
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*faa-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-undersideunder-1) ‘underside, under’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*fa[ae]fa[ae]_ ‘footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*faa-raki_ ‘use one's foot’.

Name: *fai, fai-a
Comment: Note that the _l_ of [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) form is unexpected. [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) (_sii)-fε_ ‘devilfish, ray’ is an apparent loan.

Name: *faiSa
Comment: Note [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _e_ instead of expected _i_. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _mee-Saa -Saa,_ ‘interrogative suffix’. Note also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*fee_ ‘engage in sexual intercourse, perform an action’.

Name: *fale
Comment: Note: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pal_ ‘house’ and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _bare-(aka)_ ‘boathouse’ are apparent loans, in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) case clearly from a Polynesian source.

Description: turn away, ignore the presence of others
Name: *fa-liku, fa-liku-ri-
*fanau
Comment: There may be two different roots here, or the East Chuukic languages have developed *fana- and *fféna- as analogical derivations.

Name: *faŋa
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) (_lɨ) peŋ_ ‘give to curry favor’ is presumably a loan from a Chuukic language.

Name: *f[ao]ŋ[ou]-si-
Comment: Problems here. _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*woŋ⎣iu⎦-si](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-wringout-1) ‘wring out’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri-_ ‘to snort, blow one's nose’.

Name: *fara
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pér_ ‘small sprouted coconut’ is presumably a loan from [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) or [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese). _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*far⎣ae⎦](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-lungs-1) ‘lungs’.

Description: windward platform on outrigger booms next to hull of sailing canoe
Name: *farafa
*faro, faro-ki, faro-ka
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _færfær_ ‘hold, embrace’ and _færo-s_ ‘embrace or hug him or her’ appear to be loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese). [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) should have rounded _r_.

Description: child of sibling of opposite sex
Name: *fa[sS]ua

Description: planted, to plant, a planted thing
Name: *faSo, fafaSo, faSo-ki, faSo-ka
*fatu
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pæt_ ‘cornerstone’ must be construed as a loan. See also [Marck (1994:315)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*fatu_ ‘rock, stone’.

Name: *fatu, fatufatu
Comment: The _r_ in the [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) form _per_ ‘weave’, reported by [Bender et al. 1984](Source#cldf:benderetal1984), is unexpected. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _fau-Si fau,_‘tie, bind’.

Name: *fatuku
Comment: Note loss of _k_ after _t_ rather than expected loss of _*t_ before _*k_ in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form.

Name: *fau, fau-Si
Comment: Although it might appear that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pawpéw_ ‘bind, tie’, _pawi-t_ ‘bind something’ and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pɨp_ ‘bind’, _pʷi_ ‘bind (something) could be loans from a Polynesian source such as [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _faufau_ ‘bind’, the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) pairs _yawyéw/pawpéw_ and their transitives _yawi-t/pawi-t_ have the marks of ancient doublets, with the reduplicated pair exhibiting an _a/é_ alternation, something not found in Polynesian, but expected in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) *_CaCu_ or *_CaCi_ reduplication, and also found in [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) ([Bender 1973](Source#cldf:bender1973)). Other _y/p_ doublets in _Mrs_ include _yewyew_ ‘stroke, caress’, _pewpew_ ‘sweep, brush off’ and _yir_ ‘deviate’, _pir_ ‘slip down’. These doublets point to an origin as oral/nasal grade alternants (_*p/mp_) in [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic). [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _ayʌ/pɨp_ and _awi/pʷi_ could have this same origin ([Bender 1973:463](Source#cldf:bender1973)). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _fatufatu fatu,_‘to weave, plait’.

Description: a strip of fiber for plaiting
Name: *fica
*fici, fici-ki
Comment: There appear to be two homonymous [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) roots here bearing a relationship in meaning associations like that in English between snip (with scissors or a knife) and snap (a picture or one's fingers). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _pici-ki pici,_ ‘snap, vibrate’.

Name: *fili, filifili
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _fil-(wel)_ ‘guess, conjecture, random choice’ is a loan or unrelated.

Name: *fira, fira-[kx]i
Comment: Of these the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form can be accounted for as a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) *_fili_ ([Proto-Polynesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopolynesian) _*firi_) ‘to braid, plait’, and the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms as loans from associated [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms *_biri_, _biraki_. The other Micronesian forms can be accounted for as formed from the passive and transitive (with object expressed) forms of...

Name: *fiti
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _særom_ ‘light, electricity, lightning’ and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _jórom_ ‘lightning’ are loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _jarwem_ ‘electricity, lightning, electric shock, punch, hit’. See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*fiti, fiti-ki_ ‘apply fire’.

Name: *fitu, fitu-ua
Comment: Note that the _é_ instead of _ú_ in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _féhu-(uw)_ is unexpected.

Name: *-i-
Comment: Possible doublet of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ni](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-ofpertainingto-1) ‘of, pertaining to’: generic elements in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) place names show alternation: _bekʷe-n_, _bekʷe-y_ ‘sandspit of’, _wede-n_, _wede-y_ ‘coral head of’, etc.

Description: any fish that can be caught at night
Name: *ika-ni-pʷoŋi

Description: they (independent pronoun), them (suffixed object pronoun), their (suffixed possessive pronoun)
Name: *ira
*iri, iriiri
Comment: [Geraghty’s (1990)](Source#cldf:geraghty1990) equation of [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _ii-a_ (his _ia_) with [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*ŋkuRu_ is not supported, but see [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) ? _*fa-ia_ ‘file, rub, sharpen’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) ? _*faiira_ ‘to grate’.

Name: *iri, iri-pi-
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _iri-bi_ ‘to fan’, _iri-ba_ ‘to fan (something)’ is an apparent loan from a Polynesian source, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _ili_ ‘a fan’. [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _ripóy_ ‘to fan’ is presumably a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian).

Name: *isa, isa-ŋi-
Comment: [Geraghty’s (1990)](Source#cldf:geraghty1990) deriving this from his [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*Ra[cs]i_ is questionable. _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _iso (?)_ ‘make fire by fire plow method’.

Description: dip it up, dip it out, scoop it up
Name: *isi-fi, esi-fi
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _iti-a_ ([_isi-a_]) ‘to scoop up (water), to dip, to ladle’ is presumably a loan (we do not expect _t_ here).

Description: make fire by fire plow method
Name: *iso

Description: a float on a net, light wood
Name: *iTo

Description: causative prefix, prefix forming ordinal numerals
Name: *ka-
*kacawu
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:311)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*kat’awu_. There is a problem with the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) forms.

Name: *kai₁
Comment: [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _ahey_ ‘to husk (something) with the teeth’ is an apparent loan from [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kaŋi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-eatsomething-1), [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _kana_.

Name: *kai₂
Comment: There is a possibility that some of these are loans.

Name: *kai-peti
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form makes sense as _kai_ ‘wood’ and _beti_ ‘drift’. The [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) form has reinterpreted the initial element meaning wood as a causative prefix and shortened the vowel accordingly. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _pe(tØ)ipeti pepeti, peti,_ ‘to float’.

Name: *kaka₁
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kaka₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tomakeanintrudingorinterruptingsound-1)‘to make an intruding or interrupting sound’.

Description: to make an intruding or interrupting sound
Name: *kaka₂

Description: roll or twist fiber into rope
Name: *kalo
Comment: There is a problem with the added final _a_ of the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form.

Name: *kalo
Comment: See also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*kalo](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-rollortwistfiberintorope-1) ‘roll or twist fiber into rope’. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) final consonant would call for final _a_ in reconstructed form.

Description: oil for skin or hair, anoint
Name: *kapi-sa, kapi-si
*kari
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ka-ra[wØ]u-si ka-ra[wØ]u, ra[wØ]u,_ ‘scraped, to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _kara-sa kara-si, kara,_ ‘to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*karu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscrapegrate-1) ‘to scrape, grate’, [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) [*ŋani](FormTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian-totoward-1)‘to, toward’.

Name: *karu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ka-ra[wØ]u-si ka-ra[wØ]u, ra[wØ]u,_ ‘scraped, to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _kara-sa kara-si, kara,_ ‘to scrape’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kari](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscratch-2) ‘to scratch’.

Description: white sand crab or ghost crab
Name: *karuki
*kata
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _gaas_ ‘speak a foreign language’ appears to be a loan from a Chuukic source.

Description: lee side of a sailing canoe
Name: *katea
Comment: Note that the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form could be a loan from a Polynesian source as well as directly inherited from [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian). [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _(fa)-kata_ ‘turn a ship to port’ is an apparent loan.

Name: *kau, kakau, kau-ri, kakau-ri
Comment: There are problems with the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) vowel.

Name: *kau, kau-ti, kau-ta
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) (?) _*kaúta_ ‘sibling-in-law of same sex, affinal relative.

Name: *kautu or *katuu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) reflect the second reconstruction;note that the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form may be a loan because [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) lacked a local sailing tradition.

Name: *kayinaŋa
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _kaaiŋa_ ‘ancestral residence’ is a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan), as is [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _kaaina_ ‘inhabitant, occupant, citizen’.

Name: *kiaZo
Comment: For discussion of [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) _*j_ (there _*z_), see [Goodenough (1992, fn. 8)](Source#cldf:goodenough1992). See also [Ross (1988:79, 344)](Source#cldf:ross1988).

Name: *kica
Comment: Note that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _kéj_ and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kʌt, kitε--(l)_ indicate a [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) doublet _*kita_.

Name: *kiepʷu
Comment: Note that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _kiyopʷ_ is an apparent loan from [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese) or _Pul_.

Name: *kima
Comment: It looks as if the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese), [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese), and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms are inherited reflexes of the [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:uraustronesisch), whereas the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian), and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) are loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese).

Name: *kio, kio-ri
Comment: The _s_ of the [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian) form is unexpected.

Name: *koca
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*koco₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tocut-1) ‘to cut’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kota](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-cutbreak-1) ‘cut, break’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _koo-na koo, (?)_ ‘tentacle, strand of hair or fiber’.

Name: *koca, oca
Comment: It is evident that we have doublets in [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) as well as [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic), reflecting both [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) initial _*k_ and initial _*q_. See discussion by [Geraghty (1983:161)](Source#cldf:geraghty1983).

Name: *kona
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kona](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-acatchasoffishtocatch-1) ‘a catch (as of fish), to catch’.

Description: a catch (as of fish), to catch
Name: *kona

Description: tentacle, strand of hair or fiber
Name: *koo, koo-na

Description: go aground, run on a reef
Name: *koso

Description: bivalve shell, shell knife or grater
Name: *koyi
*kulu
Comment: Note [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) form has unexpected expression of final vowel. _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) (?) _*koyikoyi_ ‘piping or whistling sound, piping bird’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*kul[iu]ŋa_ ‘plover’.

Name: *kumʷu
Comment: We cannot account for the _m_ of [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) instead of expected _mʷ_.

Description: pulled back, pull back (of foreskin or eyelid)
Name: *kura, kura-ti, kura-ta

Description: any of several kinds of fish
Name: *kuu
*laŋi
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:308)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*laŋi_. In some languages (e.g., [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese)), ‘bad weather’ meanings are to be found primarily in derived forms. Note that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _ḷaŋi-(n)_ has contrastive heavy _ḷ_ where light _l_ would be expected, with _i_ in next syllable, whereas heavy _ḷ_ is to be expected in the _ḷaŋe-(n)_ of a popular saying. Why the second vowel of this latter form is lowered in not understood, but it provides an explanation for the heavy _ḷ_s in the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) ‘bad weather’ forms.

Name: *laŋua
Comment: Loss of second vowel in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms is a problem. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) rounded _ŋʷ_ expected.

Name: *lapa
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*lúkú-lapa_ ‘ocean side (of an island or reef)’ (lit. ‘great outside’).

Name: *lau
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tokolau](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-northerlyfromthenorth-1)‘northerly, from the north’. See [Marck (1994:313)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*lau_.

Name: *l[ao]u
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) form could be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *laZe
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*ale](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-kindofcoral-1) ‘kind of coral’, [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*laxa](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-kindofcoral-2) ‘kind of coral’. See also [Marck (1994:313)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*laje_.

Name: *lea or *laya
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-raa_ ‘one width of a mat sail’ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _laa_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*⎣sS⎦aku-laara](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-swordfishmarlin-1) ‘swordfish, marlin’.

Name: *lee-, law-
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ni⎣ae⎦](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-place-1)‘place’. [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _in-_ has much the same distribution: place names, topographic features, body parts (but also forms personal names, as does _ni-_).

Name: *lele
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _rerei_ ‘good, excellent’ is a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _lelei_ ‘be good’.

Description: agentive prefix indicating “one who (does, is given to doing”) (like English suffix -er)
Name: *li-
*liki, likiliki, liki-Si
Comment: This could be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _liki-Si liki-Sa, liki,_ ‘discarded, discard’.

Name: *liki, liki-Sa, liki-Si
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _liki-Si likiliki, liki,_ ‘to strain, sift’.

Name: *liku
Comment: See also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _fa-liku-ri- fa-liku,_ ‘turn away, ignore the presence of others’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*lúkú-lapa_ ‘ocean side (of an island or reef)’ (lit. ‘great outside’).

Name: *[ln]ima
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _niim_ ‘bailer’ is an apparent loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *lima, lima-ua, lim-manu, lima-ŋawulu
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals).

Name: *l[iu]nuru
Comment: The _*nn_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic), _ll_ in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese), _l_ in [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean), and _r_ in [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) suggest that [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:uraustronesisch) _*l_, _*n_, and _*r_ followed different patterns of assimilation in the several Micronesian languages. _Cf._ [Marck (1994:325)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*luru_.

Name: *liŋoliŋo
Comment: The _n_ in the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form indicates it is not a loan from a Polynesian source. _Cf._ [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*l⎣eo⎦ŋu](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-ant-1) ant.

Name: *lukuma
Comment: (These [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms probably stand in a borrowing relationship, possibly with [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese)). _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*Lukuma_ ‘bundle’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Source#cldf:goodenough1995) and [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _suku-mi suku-ma, sukusuku,_ ‘be wrapped, a package, to wrap (something)’.

Description: be furled (of a sail), rolled or folded up
Name: *lulu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*lumi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tofold-1) ‘to fold’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*llima_ ‘lower rim of a sail’.

Name: *lumi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*lukuma](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-foldwrap-1) ‘fold, wrap’:, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*llima_ ‘lower rim of a sail’.

Name: *luuka
Comment: Short first syllable of [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) needs explanation.

Description: stative prefix indicating that what is described is an appearance or condition of being
Name: *ma-
*mai₁
Comment: Note: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _mos_ does not appear to be cognate.

Name: *maki
Comment: Note the _h_ in [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) and _Ø_ in [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) where we would expect _k_. In the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) case the _h_ suggests the word is a loan from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese). [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _ile-más_, _ili-mes_, _li-más_ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _ine-mes_ ‘love medicine’ appear to be loans from [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese).

Name: *malala
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*malle, malemale, (ka)-malemale-(a), male-di-_ ‘ground cleared of vegetation, swidden field’. And cf. [Marck (1994:322)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*mala_ and _*malala_.

Name: *maleku, maleleku, malekuleku
Comment: The reflex _n_ instead of _l_ in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) forms is unexpected. The [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) form reflects _*malakolako_; use of _-ló/-la_ directional with [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms suggests that this is contamination of earlier _*maleku-lako_ (see [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _laa lako,_ ‘go, proceed, [as directional] away’). See also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _maluoka maluoki,_ ‘forget’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ma-lie](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-forget-2) ‘forget’.

Name: *malemʷu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) substitutes _ŋʷ_ for expected _ṃʷ_, possibly in dissimilation from initial _m_ (an _ŋʷ/ṃʷ_ alternation is not uncommon);also, heavy _ḷ_ is unexpected.

Description: be efficacious, have spiritual power, efficacy, spiritual power
Name: *mana, manamana

Description: living creature of land or air
Name: *manu
Comment: Note that [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _malúk_ ‘chicken’; [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) _malúgh_ ‘chicken’; [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _malúge_ ‘chicken, hen’, and [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _malεk_ ‘chicken’ are loans, more likely from [Palauan](LanguageTable#cldf:palauan) _malk_ than from [Chamorro](LanguageTable#cldf:chamorro) _mannok_.

Name: *manu
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*manu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-livingcreatureoflandorair-1) ‘living creature of land or air’.

Name: *maraa
Comment: The East Chuukic words for ‘sail’ appear to be a locally innovated causative construction (cf. [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*yuwe](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-asail-1) ‘a sail’).

Name: *mati-ciki
Comment: The [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form (instead of expected _*mááyi-chik_ ) appears to be a loan.

Name: *mati-lapa
Comment: The [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form (instead of expected _*mááyi-nap_) could result from an old loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *ma-toa, ma-toatoa
Comment: Note the doublets in [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and the lack of expected _l_ in the [Kwaio](LanguageTable#cldf:kwaio) form.

Description: a cold or cough, breathe hard
Name: *maura
*mauri
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _mauri_ ‘be in good health’ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _mauli_.

Name: *mawolo
Comment: _Cf._ [Marck (1994:318)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*malo_ ‘concaveness, depression, valley’ (open to question because of lack of fit of [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms).

Name: *mece-a
Comment: The [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) form is felt by some speakers to be a loan from English metal [Rehg and Sohl 1979:59](Source#cldf:rehgandsohl1979). In [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean), initial _*m_ occasionally became labiovelar and is reflected by _w_ or _Ø_ — the latter especially when the following vowel develops as [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _o_.

Name: *meña
Comment: [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _mine_ ‘exist, be at a place, live , reside, there is or are’ looks like a loan.

Name: *meña-a
Comment: The raised first vowel in the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) and [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) forms in contrast with the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form attest to [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ñ_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*meña](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-thing-1) ‘thing’.

Name: *metu
Comment: Note: the _mʷ_ of [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian) and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) is presumably a secondary formation. Note also that [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _mʷúú, mʷúú-, mʷuu, mʷuu-_ ‘era, epoch’, [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _mʷeey_ ‘reign, era’ could be from the same [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) root.

Description: prefix indicating having a variable, oscillating, or variegated condition
Name: *mʷa-
*mʷakusu
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _mukʷi, mukʷikʷi_ ‘move’ looks like a loan (initial _m_ unexpected).

Description: length from elbow to finger tips
Name: *mʷa-nuu
*mʷaŋau
Comment: Note that the initial _m_ of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form is unexpected and suggests it is a loan.

Name: *mʷare
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*kamʷmʷare_ ‘carry with a shoulder pole’.

Name: *mʷata[ŋØ]ala
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _ḷ_ expected. _Cf._ also [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*taka, taka-ni_ ‘stomach, have stomach for’ and [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*daa_ ‘intestine’.

Name: *mʷ[ou]a
Comment: We have here an unusual instance in the Micronesian languages in which [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*u_ after _*mʷ_ was either lowered to _o_ or _a_ (presumably because of the following _a_) or was assimilated to the preceding _mʷ_ (see also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*mʷoe](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-sleep-2) ‘sleep’).

Name: *mʷoe
Comment: Here, again, we have the assimilation of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*o_ to a preceding _*mʷ_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) (see also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*mʷ⎣ou⎦a](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aheadgoingbefore-1) ‘ahead, going before’).

Description: feminine prefix (with personal names of women)
Name: *n[ae]i-
*namʷo
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) heavy _ṇ_ expected. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*lama₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-lagoonlake-1) ‘lagoon, lake’. See also [Marck (1994:314)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*nam’o_.

Name: *-ni
Comment: Often referred to as “the construct suffix”.

Description: verb suffix indicating acquisition or ownership
Name: *-ni, -na

Description: midrib of coconut frond or leaf
Name: *noko
*nu[sS]o
Comment: The [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) form appears to be an innovation.

Name: *ñai-Sa, ŋai-Sa
Comment: These forms are not irregular but preserve one or another of the two forms of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) and [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic), as the two [Lakalai](LanguageTable#cldf:lakalai) forms, one for past and one for future testify.

Name: *ñamʷu
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) light _n_ expected. Note that the words for ‘mosquito net’ show problems and appear to be more recent loans, at least in some cases.

Name: *ñañau
Comment: [Jackson’s (1983:374)](Source#cldf:jackson1983) statement that this is to be derived from [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) _*ñamu_ with inexplicable loss of intervocalic _*m_ is open to some question. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ñañaña ñaña,_ ‘taste, flavor’. (See also [Jackson 1983:334](Source#cldf:jackson1983)).

Name: *ŋace
Comment: [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _ŋara-aki_ ‘laugh heartily’ is an apparent loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese). _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋaco](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-palategums-1) ‘palate, gums’, [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) [*ŋace](FormTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian-edge-1) ‘edge’.

Name: *-ŋa-ratu
Comment: Note the reflex here of [Uraustronesisch](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:uraustronesisch) _*R_ in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) as _*r_ rather than as the more common reflex _*Ø_, and in [Bugotu](LanguageTable#cldf:bugotu) as _th_ rather than as the more common reflex _l_.

Name: *ŋari, ŋari-ti
Comment: See also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _li-ŋaŋari_ ‘tiny louse’; and cf. [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*kari](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-toscratch-2) ‘to scratch’, [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _ma-ŋariŋari ma-ŋari,_ ‘rough’.

Name: *ŋere, ŋereŋere
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _ma-ŋariŋari ma-ŋari,_ ‘rough’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ŋari-ti ŋari,_ ‘nibble, gnaw, crunch’, with which there has been some  confusion.

Name: *ŋii
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*ŋúnúŋúnú, mʷa-ŋúnúŋúnú_ ‘whisper’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋiTi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-chantsingbenoisylaugh-1) ‘chant, sing, be noisy, laugh’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ŋiLi_ ‘buzz, hum, make sound’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Source#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *ŋil[ai]
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*ŋúnúŋúnú, mʷa-ŋúnúŋúnú_ ‘whisper’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ŋiTi](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-chantsingbenoisylaugh-1) ‘chant, sing, be noisy, laugh’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*ŋiLi_ ‘buzz, hum, make sound’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:76)](Source#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *ŋoro
Comment: This could be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _[sS]i-ŋoro ŋoroŋoro, ŋoro,_ ‘to snore’.

Description: that (out of sight or in the past)
Name: *oo
*paca, pacapaca
Comment: See also [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) _cacapa capa, or papaca paca,_ ‘adhere’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*paca_ ‘handle, tail (of fish)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*pecee_ ‘leg’.

Name: *paca, papaca or *capa, cacapa
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*paca_ ‘handle, tail (of fish)’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _pacapaca paca,_ ‘foot, flat’.

Name: *pakewa
Comment: Note that the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) form with its unexpected _k_ could be a loan from another [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) dialect.

Name: *paŋa, paŋaki
Comment: Possibly related is [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) _paŋpaŋ_ ‘side, beside, horizontal’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pa-](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-side-1) ‘side’. _Cf._ [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*pala_ ‘tilted’.

Name: *patiki
Comment: There are problems with the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form.

Name: *pau, paupau
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _iri-pi- iri,_ ‘to fan’, and cf. [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*paLu_ ‘blow (of wind)’ posited by [Goodenough (1995:77)](Source#cldf:goodenough1995).

Name: *pawo
Comment: Note that the [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) form is unexpected here, where we would expect _*pawo_.

Name: *peka
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _fɔk, foko-(n)_ ‘feces, dung, feces of’ appears to be a loan from [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) or [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese). Note also [Lakalai](LanguageTable#cldf:lakalai) (_la)-beka-(la)_ ‘its rear end (of flying fox)’.

Name: *pekopeko or *kopekope
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kɔf, kɔfkɔf_ is an apparent loan from English. _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*fakafaka, fafaka_ ‘coughing, to cough’.

Name: *pici, pici-ki
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _fici-ki fici,_ ‘snip, cut, snap, flick’, [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) [*pici](FormTable#cldf:protowesternmicronesian-loosenedreleased-1) ‘loosened, released’.

Name: *pili
Comment: The vowel of the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form seems to pose a problem. See also [Marck (1994:318)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*pili_.

Description: come into view, begin to take shape
Name: *piŋu, pʷuŋu

Description: growth or lump under the skin, spongy core of mature coconut
Name: *piri
*pʷalu
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _kafa, kafa-i_ ‘cover, put a lid on’ are evident loans from English.

Description: taro swamp, dirt as found in taro swamp
Name: *pʷalu
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) _pʷalu_ ‘taro swamp’ ([Jackson 1986:229 fn. 4](Source#cldf:jackson1986), and [Marck 1994:316](Source#cldf:marck1994)). _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _pʷepʷelu pʷelu,_ ‘dirt, soil’.

Name: *pʷasa
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pæt_ ‘late, delayed’, instead of expected _*fæt_, is presumably a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *pʷasau
Comment: Note [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _j_ instead of expected _t_, which suggests that it is a loan, but from what source is not clear.

Name: *pʷax[ae]
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷaya_ ‘swarm of fish’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷere](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tosproutblossom-1) ‘to sprout, blossom’. _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷera](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-goorcomethroughpass-1) ‘go or come through’.

Name: *pʷelu, pʷepʷelu
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*pʷelu_ ‘dirt, soil, dirty’ ([Jackson 1986:229, fn. 4](Source#cldf:jackson1986), and [Marck 1994:316](Source#cldf:marck1994)). _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*pʷalu](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-taroswampdirtasfoundintaroswamp-1) ‘taro swamp, dirt as found in taro swamp’.

Name: *pʷepʷe
Comment: The [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form may be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan), and the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) a loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese). If so, this would be the same root as in [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _pepepe pepe,_ ‘to skip along, flit’.

Name: *pʷoi, pʷoa
Comment: There are problems here, especially the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _l_.

Name: *pʷon[ao]
Comment: See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _pʷono-ta pʷono-ti, pʷono,_ ‘be shut, blocked, to shut, block, close’.

Description: be shut, blocked, to shut, block, close
Name: *pʷono, pʷono-ti, pʷono-ta
Comment: Note that the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) initial stops are not the expected reflexes. See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷon⎣ao⎦](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-wholecomplete-1) ‘whole, complete’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*pʷalu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-coverlid-1) ‘cover, lid’.

Name: *pʷuasa
Comment: The [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) forms could be loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *pʷuli
Comment: [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) pʷun ‘shell’ are apparent loans from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese).

Name: *pʷupʷu
Comment: Note that the consetllation is named for the fish.

Name: *pʷu[sS]o
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷuro, pʷuropʷuro_ ‘bubble, foam’. [Marck (1994:315)](Source#cldf:marck1994) includes the forms in [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*pʷuro, pʷuropʷuro_ ‘bubble, foam’ with these forms in his [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*p’usop’uso_ ‘foam, froth’.

Description: to sound (when blown, as a trumpet)
Name: *pʷuu
*raŋi, raŋiraŋi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*reŋa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-turmericcolor-1) ‘turmeric color’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*caŋi_ ‘to warm oneself’. [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _raŋréŋ_ (showing vowel alternation) expected.

Description: pull out with the hands from inside something
Name: *ra[wØ]u

Description: person of or belonging to (a clan, nation, or place)
Name: *re-, ri-
*reŋa
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-reŋa_ ‘red cloth’, _reŋareŋa_ ‘to paint (something) red’ are loans from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _lega_ ‘turmeric’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*aŋo](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-curcumaturmericgingeryellow-1) ‘curcuma, turmeric, ginger, yellow’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _raŋiraŋi raŋi,_ ‘be warmed’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*yalle-pʷuta_ ‘a tree (Pittosporum)’.

Name: *ripi, ripiripi, ma-ripi
Comment: The [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) form and the [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) variants with _u_ are puzzling; if their rounding is attributed to the labial consonant, it may be of some significance that the consonant remains unvelarized.

Name: *roŋo
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _roŋoroŋo_ ‘news’ is presumed to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan). See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*roŋo_ ‘special knowledge of spells’.

Name: *ru[ao]-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*rua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-two-2) ‘two’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *ruku₂
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*roko_ ‘bend, curve’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ruku₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tipgounderwater-1) ‘tip, go under water’, [Proto-Western Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protowesternmicronesian) _ruki or riku_ ‘gather from the ground’.

Description: become aware, wake up, be surprised
Name: *rut[iu]
*[sS]aaŋa
Comment: Note that the [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) and [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese) forms are probably loans from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *[sS]afa, [sS]afa-ŋi-
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _[sS]afi₁ (?)_ ‘pick, pluck, tear off’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*daf[ei]_ ‘be open’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tafa-si tafa,_ ‘to cut in pieces, slice’.

Name: *sakau
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:308)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*sakau_. Note the doublet in [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian).

Name: *[sS]aku-laara
Comment: Note assimilation of [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _n_ and [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _l_ to following _r_. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _laya or lea (?)_‘a sail’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*⎣sS⎦aku](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-needlefish-1) ‘needlefish’.

Name: *sapa
Comment: [Pulo-Annan](LanguageTable#cldf:puloannan) _lépakaú_ ‘be capable, able, smart’ appears to be a loan from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese), perhaps from crewmen on D. D. O’Keefe’s trading boat that operated out of Yap in the late nineteenth century.

Name: *[st]apa, [st]apa[st]apa, [st]apa-ŋi
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*tape₁](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-busy-1) ‘busy’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tap[ae]-ki tap[ae],_ ‘lift up, carry, bear in one's hands’. It looks as if the Chuukic forms with initial _t_ have resulted from an early (possibly [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic)) borrowing from another Micronesian source.

Name: *sawu
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tau_ ‘enough, sufficient’ has an unexpected intial _t_, and cannot be a true cognate.

Name: *[sS]in[ae]
Comment: The reconstruction by [Marck (1994:309)](Source#cldf:marck1994) of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _* [sz]ina_ is not supported by the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) forms cited. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) (?) [*siŋa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-sunlight-1) ‘sunlight’.

Description: slice, chunk, to cut, to slice
Name: *[sS]ipa, [sS]ipa-ki
*soa
Comment: Note: there could be a problem here.

Name: *suku
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*Tuku_ ‘pound, knock’, with which there seems to have been some semantic confusion.

Description: be wrapped, a package, to wrap (something)
Name: *sukusuku, suku-ma, suku-mi
Comment: [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _sroko-m_, _sroko-mi_ ‘to wrap, envelop, wrap (something)’ appear to be loans.

Name: *sulu
Comment: We cannot account for [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _téén_, _#téénú-_ or the [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) doublet _téél_.

Name: *susu
Comment: Note that [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _thuuth_ ‘breast’ appears to be a loan from [Ulithian](LanguageTable#cldf:ulithian).

Name: *-Saa, mee-Saa
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*Safa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-whatwhatrelationship-1) ‘what? what relationship?’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _faiSa (?)_ ‘do what, what?’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*pʷa-ki-da_ ‘because, why’.

Name: *Siwa-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*Siwa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-nine-1) ‘nine’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *tafa, tafa-si
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _[sS]afi₁ (?)_ ‘pick, pluck, tear off’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _[sS]afa-ŋi- [sS]afa,_ ‘to gather, pick’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*daf[ei]_ ‘be open’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tapa-ki tapatapa, tapa,_ ‘be cut, lopped, to cut (something) off’.

Name: *tali-
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) heavy _ḷ_ results from assimilation to following directionals, which begin with heavy consonants.

Description: side dish of meat, fish, or sauce
Name: *talia
*tano
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*itano_ ‘deposited, put away’. See [Marck (1994:317)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*tano_ ‘soil, earth, ground’.

Description: from (something), away from (usually suffixed to verbs)
Name: *taŋi
*tapa, ka-tapa
Comment: This may be the same root as [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tapa-[kŋ]i tapa,_ ‘to answer’.

Description: lift up, carry, bear in ones hands
Name: *tap[ae], tap[ae]-ki
*tapa, tapa-[kŋ]i
Comment: This may be the same root as [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _ka-tapa tapa,_ ‘speak, spoken’.

Description: be cut, lopped, to cut (something) off
Name: *tapa, tapatapa, tapa-ki
*tapaka[wØ]u
Comment: [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _sepaawo_ (sic) ‘coconut leaf mat’ is clearly a loan from another Chuukic language, and the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form may be a loan from [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese).

Name: *tape₁
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tap[ae]-ki tap[ae],_ ‘lift up, carry, bear in one's hands’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _[st]apa-ŋi [st]apa[st]apa, [st]apa,_ ‘to help’.

Name: *tapʷakea
Comment: See also [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _pʷáápʷá_ ‘turtle’ and [Saipan Carolinian·T](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancaroliniant) _pʷáápʷá_ ‘turtle’, which may well be derived from _*pʷakea_.

Name: *tara
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tataro_ ‘to pray’ and _taro-mauri_ ‘worship’ are loans from Polynesian, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _talo_ ‘to pray’ (obsolete).

Name: *tara, tara-[sS]i
Comment: Geraghty’s reconstruction relies heavily on the Micronesian forms, which he seems to misinterpret.

Name: *taraki
Comment: [Yapese](LanguageTable#cldf:yapese) _tarég_ ‘to sail’ is evidently a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: *tari
Comment: Expressed final vowel without suffixed form in [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese), [Pingilapese](LanguageTable#cldf:pingilapese), and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) poses problem. _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _atarei (?)_ ‘child’.

Name: *tau₃
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _ae_ ‘who (relative pronoun)’ appears to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) (_i)-ai_ ‘who (relative pronoun)’.

Description: any of several kinds of sea bass
Name: *tawia
*tawu-₁
Comment: (The saw- in certain [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) high titles is probably a Polynesian loan). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tau₂](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-seasonsun-1) ‘season, sun’ and [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _tawu₂ (?)_ ‘clan, family’. There are problems.

Name: *tawu or *co[wØ]a-
Comment: The [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) and [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) forms are incompatible and probably do not both belong in this set. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*tautu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-porcupinefish-1) ‘porcupine fish’.

Name: *telu, telu-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Name: *tiku or *tuki
Comment: Note that _Ø_ is the expected reflex of _*t_ in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms. The _wúkú-_ in [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese) _wúkú-(par)_ and [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _wúkú-(chcha)_, _wúkú-(pak)_ appear to be the root for ‘tail’ (see [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*iku](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-tail-1) ‘tail’) rather than this one.

Name: *t[iu]pʷu
Comment: Note that [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) _dipʷ, dipʷi-(n)_ ‘exogamous matrilineal clan’ is presumably a loan.

Name: *tiro, tiro-ŋi
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _tiro-a_ ‘to inspect, scrutinize (something)’ is a loan from a Polynesian source, e.g., [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _tilotilo_ ‘look, glance’. Note the unexpected absence of an initial consonant (_t_ or _s_) in the [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) form, which may be a loan from [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian).

Name: *tiSaki
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*[kØ]a[tØ]ieki_ ‘to ask’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*katia, katitia_ ‘to ask, a question’.

Name: *to[ae]
Comment: Inclusion of [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:woleaian) _tóó-(shigi)_ ‘careful treatment, careful consideration’ in this series ([Bender et al. 1984](Source#cldf:benderetal1984), [Geraghty 1990](Source#cldf:geraghty1990)) is not justifiable. There are problems here.

Name: *toki
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) doublet (_te)-toki_ ‘chisel’ would appear to be a loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _to’i_ ‘adze’, since it does not show the loss of _t_ before _k_.

Name: *toko, toko-na
Comment: Note: [Chuukese](LanguageTable#cldf:chuukese), [Mortlockese](LanguageTable#cldf:mortlockese), and [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese) _wóók, wóku-n_ ‘cane, cane of’, may be related but are not inherited forms.

Name: *tuki, tukituki
Comment: Note that _Ø_ is the expected reflex in the [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian) and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms.

Name: *tuna
Comment: [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _teṇʷ_ ‘freshwater eel’ is an evident loan from [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) — these eels are not found in the Marshalls but are known from the Eastern Carolines.

Name: *Tiri
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _mim_ ‘urinate’ is either a loan from a Polynesian source or an inherited reflex of [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protooceanic) _*mimi_ ([Proto-Polynesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopolynesian) _mimi_, [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:fijian) _mii, mimi_).

Name: *Toka
Comment: [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) _toka_ ‘be placed upon, take passage, get on’ is clearly a loan from a Polynesian source.

Description: general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)
Name: *-ua
*uluŋa
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*ulu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-extremitytoptiphead-1) ‘extremity, top, tip, head’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*uluulu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-pillowuseapillow-1) ‘pillow, use a pillow’.

Name: *umʷa, imʷa
Comment: Note that [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _lɔm_ is a probable loan (source ?).

Description: hair, feathers, scales, remove (hair or scales)
Name: *una, unauna, una-fi
*ura
Comment: Note that [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-ura_ is an apparent loan from [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _ula_.

Name: *u[sS]a, u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a-na
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _u-Taki u-Ti,_ ‘carry’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _wua-ta wua-ti, wuawua, wua,_ ‘carry, convey, transport’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’.

Name: *u-Ti, u-Taki
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _u[sS]a-na u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a, (?)_ ‘cargo, load’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _wua-ta wua-ti, wuawua, wua,_ ‘carry, convey, transport’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’.

Name: *wai
Comment: One of these could be a loan from the other.

Name: *waka
Comment: There is no basis for [Geraghty’s (1990)](Source#cldf:geraghty1990) reconstruction of [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _*aka_ ‘vein, sinew’. See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ua₁ (?)_ ‘tendon, vein’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _wakara waka,_ ‘root’.

Name: *walu, walu-ua
Comment: See [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*-ua](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-generalclassifierincountingsuffixedtonumerals-1) ‘general classifier in counting (suffixed to numerals)’.

Description: to beat, to strike with an object
Name: *w[ao]pʷo

Description: balloon fish, puffer fish, be large
Name: *wasi, wasiwasi

Description: toward or in direction of person addressed
Name: *watu
*waxa₁
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) [*wa⎣xØ⎦a](FormTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian-crosspiece-1) ‘crosspiece’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _wua-ta wua-ti, wuawua, wua,_ ‘carry, convey, transport’.

Name: *woca
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:314)](Source#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _ot’a_, which he sees as cognate with Proto-Central Pacific _*voda_ ‘rocks in sea’.

Name: *woŋ[iu]-si
Comment: There is no basis for [Geraghty’s (1990)](Source#cldf:geraghty1990) Micronesian reflexes of his [Proto-Eastern Oceanic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protoeasternoceanic) _*ŋkiRi_ ‘squeeze’. _Cf._ [Proto-Central Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) _f[ao]ŋ[ou]-si- (?)_ ‘blow (one's nose)’, [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protochuukic) _*ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri-_ ‘to snort, blow one's nose’.

Name: *wotu
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*watu](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-towardorindirectionofpersonaddressed-1) ‘toward or in direction of person addressed’.

Name: *wua, wuana
Comment: There is an apparent problem with the the initial _f_ of [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean).

Name: *wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta
Comment: _Cf._ also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _u[sS]a-na u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a, (?)_ ‘cargo, load’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _u-Taki u-Ti,_ ‘carry’, [Proto-Pohnpeic-Chuukic](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protopohnpeicchuukic) _*waa_ ‘carry it, convey it, transport it’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*waxa₁](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-aframe-1) ‘a frame’.

Description: earth oven, bake in an oven
Name: *wumʷu, wumʷu-ni-

Description: a reef fish prized as food
Name: *wumʷu-lau
Comment: _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) _wumʷu-ni- wumʷu,_ ‘earth oven, bake in an oven’.

Name: *wupʷu-₂
Comment: Note that the [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) form could also derive from [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:gilbertese) (_te)-ubwu_ ‘nose, snout’. _Cf._ [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable?is_proto#cldf:protomicronesian) [*wupʷa](FormTable#cldf:protomicronesian-bellyabdomentorso-1) ‘belly, abdomen, torso’.

Name: aúrú
Comment: Ksr ɛir, glossed as ‘north’ in dictionary, is a probable loan (see PMc *afaŋi ‘north’). Marck (1994:323) reconstructs PMc *auru, including the Ksr forms whose r is unexpected.

Name: cee, ceecee
Comment: Cf. PMc *cece, cecece ‘shake, tremble’, PCk *cééú ‘continuously widespread’, PCk *caka-i-, ccaka-i- ‘chase, pursue’.

Name: coko, li-coko
Comment: Note that Mrs tékwékwkwékw ‘clucking of a hen’ has an initial t instead of expected d and is, therefore, an apparent loan from Pon or Chk.

Description: negative imperative aspect marker, lest (purposeful future negative)
Name: -de
dera-úna
Comment: See PMc *una, unauna, una-fi ‘hair, feathers, scales, remove (hair or scales)’.

Description: the number one, one (in serial counting)
Name: edda, #eeda

Description: pinch or squeeze with the fingers
Name: fadi, fadi-ki-
fawo-ni-pei
Comment:
See PMc *fawo ‘surface, on’, PMc *-ni ‘of, pertaining to’, PCMc *pei ‘stone structure’.
The Pon, Mok, and Chk forms appear to be cognate; the remainder are clearly loans from the Pon or Chk forms.

Description: engage in sexual intercourse, perform an action
Name: fee
fin[ei]
Comment: Cf. also PMc *fi- ‘mutually’, PMc *fira, fira-[kx]i ‘to twist’, PWMc *fiŋi-[sS]i ‘to twist, twirl’.

Name: -ik[ae]
Comment: Cf. PCMc *-itaki ‘counter for tens’, PMc *-ŋawulu ‘unit of ten (in counting)’.

Name: ? kaúlú
Comment: Cf. Ksr on ‘sing, song’. @Cf. PWMc *kau, kakau, kau-ri, kakau-ri ‘call, call to’, PMc *alele ‘to reckon, sing’.

Description: piping or whistling sound, piping bird
Name: ? koyikoyi

Description: back or nape of head and neck
Name: -kú-
Comment:
Cf. PMc *ua3 ‘neck’.
There are problems with reconstruction here, since the form has been preserved only in compounds outside of Chk and reinterpreted along the way.

Description: have something caught in the throat
Name: laawa
lec[ae], lecelec[ae]
Comment: Cf. also PCk *llecú ‘make a loud noise’.

Name: ? ma
Comment: It is unclear what to make of this.

Description: any of several species of fern with alternating leaves
Name: (ka)-maarek[ae]
ŋúd[iú]
Comment: Cf. also PCk *ŋúdú, ŋŋúdú ‘strong, resistant’ (perhaps same root) and PCk *ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri‘to snort, blow one's nose’.

Name: ? paar, para-, parata
Comment: The PuA d instead of t is unexpected, as is the p instead of f in the Chuukic forms, so we may be dealing with a chain of loans here. See Marck (1994:311) Index PMc *para(ta).

Name: palúa1
Comment: Yap piluw ‘navigator, navigation’ is presumably a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: pede
Comment: Marck’s (1994:315) reconstruction of PPC *pese based on the Mrs form is open to question.

Name: pirafa
Comment: The transitive forms in Wol and PuA are unexpected.

Name: poroto
Comment: The initial po- is a problem here.

Description: right, correct, as it should be
Name: pwuŋu
pwure
Comment: The Chk form may be a loan from Pon.

Name: rata
Comment: Marck (1994:322) reconstructs PMc *rata by adding Kir ata ‘broad as a mat or cloth, width of land’ to this set of forms.

Description: in regard to, on behalf of, at
Name: ree-

Description: gate, door that may be opened or closed
Name: riciŋa
taka, taka-ni
Comment: Cf. PCMc *taa, taa-ni ‘to like, be fond’, PMc *tia ‘stomach, belly, abdomen’, PCk *daa ‘intestine’.

Description: to break, crack, hatch an egg
Name: tawaa, ka-tawaa
Tuku
Comment:
Cf. PMc *suka, with which there seems to have been some semantic confusion.
Note that Pul súk (sic) ‘steel (for striking flint and steel)’, súkú-ú-(w) ‘strike it (as flint and steel)’ is probably a loan from Chk.

Name: úkú
Comment: Cf. PMc *iku ‘tail’, PCk *úkúúkú, úkú-fi ‘cut off, chop off’.

Description: carry it, convey it, transport it
Name: waa
Comment: Cf. also PMc ? *u[sS]a, u[sS]a-ni, u[sS]a-na ‘cargo, load’, PMc *u-Ti, u-Taki ‘carry’, PMc *wua, wuawua, wua-ti, wua-ta ‘carry, convey, transport’, PMc *waxa1 ‘a frame’.

Name: wairaki
Comment: Note the h and s in the Pul, Crn, Crl, and Wol forms may indicate that they are loans from a Chk source in which *ki has shifted to si.

Name: wau
Comment: Cf. Marck (1994:320) PMc *wao based only on the Pon form.

Description: name of a sky god (lit. stamping fellow)
Name: wolo-faadi
Comment:
See PPC *wolo ‘male person’, PMc *faa, faa-[sS]i ‘apply the sole of the foot’.
(Hambruch 1926, 2:105)

Name: wono-yik[ae]
Comment: See PMc *wono- ‘six’ and PPC *-ik[ae] ‘counter for tens’.

Name: woro-
Comment: Cf. also PWMc *oro ‘be, exist’, PWMc *Toro-mi ‘suck up (something)’.

Description: be hung up, to hang (something) up
Name: cana-k, cana-ki
Comment: See also PCk *c[ae]ŋaki, cc[ae]ŋaki ‘hang, be suspended’.

Description: to kiss, make a sucking sound
Name: mici-ki
mwaaca
Comment: Cf. also PCk *maada ‘a garden’, PMc *maata, maataata ‘cleared space’.

Name: ŋala, ŋalaŋala
Comment: Marck’s (1994:314) reconstruction of PMc *ŋalu ‘ocean swell, billow’ from this Mok form and Mrs ŋél is open to some question.

Name: palia
Comment: Except as loans from some undetermined source, these forms cannot be cognate with Geraghty’s (1990) PEO *wari[cz]a ‘two days ago/hence’ (Saa wa’ite and Ula walita ‘day after tomorrow’; Aro (na) warita ‘long ago, some time ago’; Kwa kwalita ‘three days ago’; Lak uaisa ‘day after tomorrow’).

Name: uutV
Comment: Geraghty (1990) sees this as a reflex of his PEO *qu[cz]uRi ‘to follow’. Kir iri ‘to go in company’, which he also equates with this, is cognate with Chk fiti (PMc *fiSi) and does not belong in this set.

Name: afakúra
Comment: This may be an East Chuukic innovation.

Description: name of Elato (island and atoll) in Central Carolines
Name: alaado

Description: the three stars in Orion's belt
Name: alúalú

Description: to know, be familiar with something
Name: ama
apa
Comment: Note our assumption that the Mrt, Stw, and Wol independent forms are secondary formations from the bound form with possessive suffix, which would be the one in most common use. Cf. also PMc *kapa ‘bundle of something’ It is possible to see a semantic connection between rolled up mats, bundles, bundles of grass put between babies’ legs for waste management, the rolling up of woven cloth on the loom-beam, and the cloth itself, especially that of a kind used for babies’ waste disposal.

Name: api
Comment: Cf. PMc *afi, afi-Si- ‘carry on the hip or under the arm’.

Name: cao-pwuda
Comment: See PCMc *cao ‘group, group member’, PCMc *pwusa, pwusa-ka ‘bad, improper’.

Name: cappa
Comment: The PCk form is to be understood as from an older *ca-papa (see PCMc *ca- ‘state of being’).

Description: to massage (after a fall or bruise)
Name: caúcaú
Comment:
Cf. PMc ? *ma-caucau ‘soft’.
Possibly refers to the application of leaves in massage (see PMc *cau ‘leaf’).

Description: name of Tinian Island, Mariana Islands
Name: ccinialo

Description: lift with the hands, make erect
Name: cife, cife-di
Comment: Note also Pon tip ‘be full after eating (honorific)’.

Name: coroŋo
Comment: See PMc *roŋo ‘hear, listen’, PCMc *ca- ‘state of being’.

Description: mound, hill, mountain, name of Chuuk (Truk)
Name: cuku
Comment: Pon ruk ‘Chuuk’ is presumably a loan, as is Mok ruk, Mrs rikw, and Ksr ruk. Cf. Kir (te)-riki ‘land formed by the washing up of sand’. See also Marck (1994:320) PCk *t’uku.

Name: cúyi-falú
Comment: See PMc *cuyi‘ bone’, PWMc *falu2 ‘prick, pointed object’.

Name: daa
Comment: Cf. PPC *taka, taka-ni ‘stomach, have stomach for’.

Name: d(ae)r(ae)
Comment: There are problems here with the Chk and Pul forms.

Description: go on all fours, crawl, climb
Name: daú, daú-ki
Comment: See also PCk *daú-llawa ‘to creep, crawl on hands and knees’.

Description: to creep, crawl on hands and knees
Name: daú-llawa
Comment: See also PCk *daú, daú-ki ‘go on all fours, crawl, climb’.

Name: ddaf[ei], dafi-i-
Comment: Cf. also PMc *[sS]afi, PPC *dafa, dafa-ŋi, PMc *tafa, tafa-Si.

Description: go about gathering or in search of something
Name: ddari, li-ddari

Description: to move close along or over
Name: deka, deka-ri or dake, dake-ri-
dikadika
Comment: See also PCk *dika, dikka ‘cut and lift off or out, peel’.

Description: cut and lift off or out, peel
Name: dika, dikka
dila, dila-ŋi-
Comment: See also PCk *dila-wupwa ‘distance from outstretched finger-tip to mid-chest (lit. “breast split”, cloth yard, a measure in counting)’.

Description: distance from outstretched finger-tip to mid-chest (lit. “breast split”, cloth yard, a measure in counting)
Name: dila-wupwa
Comment: See also PCk *dila, dila-ŋi- ‘chop lengthwise, split’, PMc *wupwa ‘belly, abdomen, torso’.

Name: dili
Comment: Cf. PCk *dili-mwaúlú ‘a fish’, PWMc *sili ‘louse egg, nit’.

Name: dili-mwaúlú
Comment: Cf. PCk *dili ‘a small fish’, PMc *mwonu ‘squirrel fish’.

Name: dupwu3
Comment: Cf. also PMc *Suu, SuuSuu, Suu-fi- ‘dive, bathe’.

Name: ? faa-
Comment: See also PCk *caka-i-, ccaka-i- ‘chase, pursue’, PMc *faa, faa-[sS]i ‘apply the sole of the foot’, PCk *dapwa, dapwe-e- ‘follow’.

Description: footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom
Name: fa[ae]fa[ae]
Comment: Cf. PMc *faa- ‘underside, under’, PMc *faa, faa-[sS]i ‘apply the sole of the foot’, PCk *faa-raki ‘use one's foot’.

Name: faaniyape
Comment: We cannot account for the r in the Chk forms except as a reinterpretation of flapped intervocalic n.

Name: faa-raki
Comment: See also PCk *faa- ? ‘go on foot’, PMc *faa, faa-[sS]i ‘apply the sole of the foot’, PCk *fa[ae]fa[ae] ‘footbrace in the form of a stationary block of wood under the warp beam of a loom’.
