Description: name of Faraulep (island and atoll), Central Carolines
Name: facaúlapa
? fa-ia
Comment:
Cf. PMc *iri, iriiri ‘rub, scrub’.
Chk feyiyán ‘file’ is an apparent loan from English, and the Wol form may be, too.

Name: fako[ln]a
Comment: Note also PCk *fakola ‘grow, be reared’, PCk ? *fano ‘pampered’.

Description: name of an island in the Hall Islands (lit. spirit lowland or reef)
Name: fana-anútú
Comment: See PCk *fana1 ‘lowland or reef’, PMc *anitu ‘god, spirit’.

Name: ? fano
Comment: Note also PCk *fakola ‘grow, be reared’, PCk *fako[ln]a ‘longing’.

Description: put over the shoulders (as a lei)
Name: fare
fari1
Comment:
Cf. PCMc *fari- ‘less than ...’.
We cannot account for the n in the Chk form except as a reinterpretation deriving from sandhi phenomena.

Description: carving along side of a canoe
Name: fari2
faú
Comment: Kir bwoou is a loan from a Polynesian source.

Description: raised seat or platform on a sailing canoe
Name: ? fa[uú]naki
fi-di-
Comment: See PMc *fi- ‘mutually’. Cf. PPC *fin[ei] ‘wrapped, bound up’.

Name: fútúú-te-mwakúdú
Comment: May be a post-PCk innovation confined to eastern portion of Chuukic area.

Description: name of Ifaluk (island and atoll), Central Carolines
Name: ifalúkú
iici, ici-, ici, ici-i-
Comment: These could be a chain of loans. Writing was introduced in the Central Carolines by a castaway missionary late in the nineteenth century. It was first done there by carving letters in wood. The source of the word remains unknown.

Name: ika-falúfalú
Comment: See PMc *ika, ika-na‘fish’, PWMc *falu2 ‘prick, pointed object’.

Name: itano
Comment:
Cf. also PMc *tano ‘ground, low’.
The unexpected ó in the Chk forms makes sense if we see these forms as arising from a reinterpretation of *isón (<*isano) by analogy with Chk iseni, iseyis (see PMc *ita, itaita ‘deposit, pile up’).

Name: kacii
Comment: Chk á instead of e suggests the possibility of a loan from Wol (palm toddy was known but not ordinarily made in Chuuk). Toddy making was probably introduced from the Philippines into the Western Carolinian atolls and thence spread to Chuuk and Yap. The Mrs terms jedan and jekaréw are loans from Kir te-ran (‘liquid’) and te-karewe (‘sweet or unfermented [coconut sap]’), Kir having developed its own distinct vocabulary for toddy making (see Bender 1981). See also PCk *cii, cii-ri ‘drip, sprinkle’, on which root this may be a causative construction.

Name: kadelú
Comment: See also PMc ? *mawa ‘yawn, be open mouthed’.

Name: kaewa[ln]ú
Comment: The name seems to mean ‘forest tree’, cf. PCk *kae ‘stick, pole’, PMc *walu ‘vegetation, forest’.

Name: ka-falli
Comment: Cf. PWMc *-ali, -aliali, mwa-aliali ‘circle, circling, dizzy’, PCk *mwaali ‘confused, mistaken’.

Name: kapilipili
Comment: The derivation of this is obscure. It could be a Chuukic innovation from a corruption of PMc *kapi ‘bottom, butt end’ (cf. Mok kɔpi-n pɔ ‘elbow’; Ksr kapi-n pæo-l ‘his elbow’; PMc *pau ‘hand, arm, wing’), but then the apparent PCk *l rather than *n is a problem.

Description: neonate, newly born animal, newly hatched bird
Name: kappa, kappa-na
karafa
Comment: Note that Ksr kʌraf ‘kind of fish’ is an apparent loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: [kØ]a[tØ]ieki
Comment: Cf. PMc *tiSaki ‘to ask’, PCk *katia, katitia ‘to ask, a question’.

Description: tear or peel with the teeth
Name: [kØ]aTe-i-, [kØ]aTTe-i-
Comment: See also PMc *etieti ‘to peel with the teeth’.

Name: ? kaTi
Comment: Note that the Chk name may be a loan from Wol.

Description: sibling-in-law of same sex, affinal relative
Name: ? kaúta
Comment: cf. PMc *kau, kau-ti, kau-ta ‘fishhook, catch with hook’.

Name: keci
Comment: Kir (te)-kimwoa ‘rat’ is a loan from Sam ‘imoa, and Kir (te)-kiri ‘dog’ is an apparent loan from a Pn source (PPn *kulii; Sam ‘uli) and is not cognate with these words for ‘rat’.

Description: woman's belt or necklace of shell beads
Name: kini
kipwa
Comment: Note the loss of *k in the Chk, Pul, Crl, and Crn forms is unexpected.

Description: to pick things up by hand
Name: ? kiri, kiri-i-
kú[ln]arú
Comment: Note the assimilation of n or l to a following r in Chk, Pul, Crl, Crn, Wol, Ksr, and Pon.

Name: kul[iu]ŋa
Comment: Cf. PPC ? *koyikoyi ‘piping or whistling sound, piping bird’, PMc *kulu ‘kind of bird’.

Description: high tide or be hight tide
Name: kúnna

Description: long ago, ancient times, the old days
Name: laamwo

Description: a catch of fish, to catch (fish)
Name: liapa, liapa-ni

Description: clean, neat, beautiful, to clean or neaten (something)
Name: lima, limalima, lima-kaccú, lima-di

Description: kind of unicorn fish (lit. rough to the touch one)
Name: li-maadaada
li-mwa-doŋo
Comment: There are problems with the Chk form.

Name: ? [ln]iwetta
Comment: This could well be an intra-Chuukic loan.

Name: llecú
Comment: Cf. PPC *lec[ae], lecelec[ae] ‘to rap, strike sharply’.

Name: llema, lema-ti-
Comment: Cf PCMc *ñama ‘make a noose or snare’.

Name: lodoa, lodoa-lapa, lodoa-ara, lodoa-afaŋi
Comment: Note also Ksr rɔtɔ ‘w.’ with its unexpected intial r, which marks it a probable loan, along with other direction terms. Marck (1994:324) includes it in his reconstruction of PMc *losowa.

Description: ocean side (of an island or reef) (lit. great outside)
Name: lúkú-lapa
lúwa, lúwa-di
Comment: See also PCk ? *malúa ‘loose’, PCk *ma-lúalúa ‘calm’, PCk *lúwaa ‘be calm (of sea or weather)’.

Name: lúwaa
Comment:
See also PCk *ma-lúalúa ‘calm’, PCk *lúwa, lúwa-di ‘loose, swung out’.
Cf. Marck (1994:311) PMc *malua ‘calm’.

Name: maa
Comment: See also PMc *ma-toa, ma-toatoa ‘firm, hard, strong’.

Name: maada
Comment: Cf. also PMc *maata, maataata ‘cleared space’, PPon *mwaada ‘cleared land, garden’.

Name: maa-yi-rúú
Comment: See PMc *rut[iu] ‘become aware, wake up, be surprised’, PCk *maa ‘behavior, manner, habit’, and PCk *mwa-úcúúcú or *mwa-icúicú ‘to shake’.

Name: ma-caro
Comment: See also Marck’s (1994:316) PCk *mat’aro. Note assimilation of following r to preceding ch in Chk.

Name: ma-dawudawu
Comment:
Cf. PMc *ma-[sS]aLu, ma-[sS]aLu[sS]aLu ‘smooth (of surface) ’ posited by Goodenough (1995:77).
We consider the mw of Chk to be a secondary development.

Description: finger joint, finger between tip and second knuckle, finger between tip and first knuckle
Name: makoto, makoto-lapa, makoto-ciki
malla
Comment: Marck’s (1994:312) PMc *mala(wa) ‘dawn’ is not supported by evidence outisde Chuukic languages.

Description: ground cleared of vegetation, swidden field
Name: malle, malemale, (ka)-malemale-(a), male-di-
Comment:
Cf. PMc *malala ‘area without vegetation’. 
Note that Chk (nee)-man ‘inland (especially in relation to settlement areas), ashore, pertaining to land’ and Mrt ‘lee-mal ‘land’ do not go with these. See also Marck (1994:322) PCk *malemale.

Name: ? malúa
Comment: Cf. Also PCk *lúwa, lúwa-di ‘loose, swung out’.

Name: ma-lúalúa
Comment: See also PCk *lúwa, lúwa-di ‘loose, swung out’, PCk *lúwaa ‘be calm (of sea or weather)’, PCk *ma-lúú, ma-lúúlúú ‘tired, fatigued’.

Name: marata
Comment: Yap marat ‘bitter (of betel nut)’ is a loan from Uli.

Description: kind of snapper fish (lit. bloody eye or face)
Name: ? mata-ccaa
mata-paca
Comment: See PMc *mata ‘eye, face’, PWMc *paca, papaca or *capa, cacapa ‘adhere’.

Name: ma[tØ]e-[iØ]-lééléé
Comment: See PMc *mate ‘die, lose consciousness’, PMc *lau ‘pool, have liquid’.

Name: ma[tØ]e-pwud[ao]
Comment:
See PMc *mate and PMc *pwusa, pwusaka. 
Note that the Wol form in this case may be a loan from Pul or Chk.

Name: ma[uú]ta
Comment:
Cf. PMc *maawa ‘a fish’, PCMc *maoko ‘a fish’;
It is not clear that the Wol form belongs in this series.

Description: give off steam or odor in cooking
Name: ? mawa
mwaali
Comment: See also PWMc *-ali, -aliali, mwa-aliali ‘circle, circling, dizzy’, PCk *ka-falli ‘be careful of, attend to’.

Description: be held, caught, to hold, grip
Name: mwacú, (ka)-mwacú-(ú)
mwa-úcúúcú or mwa-icúicú
Comment: See PMc *ucuucu, ucu-ki ‘shake’. Cf. PCk *maa-yi-rúú ‘be startled, surprised’.

Name: mwel[ie]
Comment: Note the ee and e of the Chk forms are unexpected for a stem vowel i and suggest that the Chk forms result from borrowing from another Chuukic language.

Name: mweŋ[ae]ya
Comment: Note that Jackson (1986:230, fn. 5) reconstructs PMc *mwaŋea.

Name: mwiri-i-dupwu
Comment: See PWMc *mwuri‘behind’, PCk *dupwu3 ‘set (of sun), go down’. These may be independent constructions from the same roots.

Name: mwor[ae]
Comment: Cf. PMc *maura ‘a cold or cough, breathe hard’.

Description: feminine prefix (with personal names of women)
Name: na-
nekú, nnekú, nekúnekú
Comment: Cf. PPC *nekú, nekúnekú ‘store, put away’, PMc *l[iu]ku ‘trust, believe, be confident’.

Description: afraid, be afraid of, a coward
Name: niwa, niwa-idi
nne- or lle-
Comment: Cf. also PCk *nna ‘appear’, PCMc *lelesa ‘true, real’, PMc *loo, loo-Si ‘to see, behold’.

Description: them (third person plural inanimate object pronoun)
Name: -nni

Description: stay, remain, be (at or in a place or time)
Name: noko
Comment: Note that Jackson’s (1991:101) attribution to a POc *nopo is not supported by the Wol form.

Name: ŋaTa, ŋaTaŋaTa
Comment: Note that PuA and Sns d indicates PCk *T.

Description: name of Ngulu (island and atoll), Western Carolines
Name: ? ŋelúwa
ŋúTú, ŋŋúTú-, ŋúTú-ri-
Comment: Cf. PPC *ŋúd[iú] ‘congested, tightly packed’, PCMc ? *f[ao]ŋ[ou]-si- ‘blow (one's nose)’.

Name: paca
Comment: See also PWMc *paca, papaca or *capa, cacapa ‘adhere’, PMc *paca, pacapaca ‘foot, flat’.

Name: pala
Comment: Cf. PCMc *paŋa, paŋaki ‘crossways’, PCk *paTo, paTTo ‘motionless, still’.

Name: parata
Comment: PuA panada ‘be windy, blow’ looks like a loan from another Chuukic language.

Name: péé, péé-n[iu]
Comment: See also PCk *pééra ‘coconut shell container’, PCk *ppéé or *ppaú ‘play with a ball’, PMc *peo ‘brush aside’.

Name: perewu
Comment: Marck’s (1994:317) combining these forms with Kir bwaa and Mrs bwar to reconstruct PMc *p’aro is open to some question.

Description: name of present Pikelot Island, Central Carolines (meaning sandy islet)
Name: piike
Comment:
See PMc *pike ‘sand islet’.
Note that here Chk preserves the final k.

Name: ppéé or ppaú
Comment: See also PCk *péé, péé-n[iu] ‘empty (as a container)’, PMc *peo ‘brush aside’.

Name: ? pwaaú2
Comment: PuA papwu and Ksr pæmpu are loans from English.

Name: pwaŋi2
Comment: Cf. PCk *pwaŋi1 ‘art of rigging and construction’.

Name: pwiri, pwpwiri
Comment: Geraghty (1990) wrongly infers a PMc *piri from the Wol form and equates it with his PEO *puRu ‘make a trumpet noise’.

Name: pwolowado
Comment: The initial vowel of the Wol form is unexpected and suggests it may be an old loan.

Name: pwpweye
Comment: Cf. also PMc ? *pweLe ‘blister’ posited by Goodenough (1995:77).

Description: name of Pulo Anna Island, Western Carolines
Name: ? pwpwulo
Comment: Note that some of these could be loans as easily as inherited forms.

Name: pwuku or pwúkú
Comment: Cf. also PMc *pwere ‘to sprout, blossom’, PCk *pwikili ‘seed’.

Name: pwuyu
Comment: Cf. also Marck (1994:319) who reconstructs PMc *p’ulu ‘fall, flow’ while noting the PCk irregular loss of PMc *l, and Goodenough (1995:77) who posits PMc *pwuLu ‘flow’, for which this loss would be regular.

Name: rakici
Comment: Mrs likwej, liwej ‘Callophyllum’ appears to be a loan from a Chuukic source.

Name: ree, reeree
Comment: See also PCk *ratirati, rati-i- ‘cut, remove by cutting’.

Name: riciŋa
Comment: Cf. PPC *riciŋa ‘gate, door that may be opened or closed’.

Description: name of Satawan Island, Mortlock Islands, and of Satawal Island, Central Carolines
Name: tadawana

Description: have skin affected by sea water
Name: tadi-kkaŋi
takullu
Comment: Looks like a loan from somewhere.

Name: ta-rama
Comment: Ksr sa-rom ‘electricity’ would appear to be a loan from Mrs. See PMc *rama ‘bright, luminous’ and PAn *damaR ‘torch’ (Ross 1988).

Description: a star or constellation in Corvus
Name: tarepwalú
Comment: Pon sɛripwɛl ‘C.’ (Bender et al. 1984) is a probable loan from a Chuukic source.

Description: to go along the side of (an island)
Name: tawa-yi-
ta[wØ]ia-awa
Comment: See PWMc *tawia ‘any of several kinds of sea bass’.

Name: tawuwafaŋi
Comment: Cf. Yap f’aaŋ ‘kind of eel’, from which it may be derived.

Name: terú1
Comment:
See also PCk *terú2 ‘to say’.
The first vowel of the Chk form is unexpected and this form may be a loan from another Chuukic dialect.

Name: tiri
Comment:
Cf. PMc *iri, iriiri ‘rub, scrub’.
Note that Ksr iri-i ‘masturbate’ may be a loan from Chk via the Trust Territory’s high school that was located on Chuuk for a while after World War II.

Name: Tora
Comment: Cf. Marck’s (1994:313) reconstruction of PPC *tora ‘morning’ is open to some question.

Name: Touk[ae]
Comment: Chk pwúnúsuuk is a loan from the English version of the name.

Description: a constellation in Cassiopeia (lit. fishs tail)
Name: úkú-ni-ika
úle, úl(ea)úl(ea), (ka)-úle, (ta)-úle
Comment: PuA sa-úla is clearly a loan from Wol.

Description: name of Ulithi (island and atoll), Western Carolines
Name: úlú-diwo

Description: name of Ulul Island in Namonuito Atoll
Name: unouno
Comment: The Crl form appears to be a loan.

Name: wayidi
Comment: See also PCk *wayi, wayi-di ‘be pulled, pull, pull on’, Chk weyiye-rek ‘trolling on the open sea’.

Description: to scoop, scrape out, dig (as with claws)
Name: ? wedi2
Comment: The Chk form has unexpected e instead of i.

Name: weewee
Comment: See also PMc *wee ‘be alike, same, equivalent’.

Description: name of Olimarao (island and atoll), Central Carolines
Name: weni-maraawu
yaado
Comment: Her name appears to be cognate with PEO *qazo ‘sun, day’ (PPn qaho ‘day’; Saa sato; Bug aho; PKb *hazo ‘sun, day’); UAn *qajaw ‘sun’. The name of her husband (Uli yól) appears to reflect PEO *qalo ‘sky, heaven, sun’. See PMc *alo ‘sun’.

Description: oops! oh! (exclamation at having mispoken or remembered something forgotten)
Name: yaakú
yaloyalo
Comment: See also PMc *alo ‘sun’, PMc *reŋa ‘turmeric color’, PMc *aŋo ‘curcuma, turmeric, ginger, yellow’.

Description: wooden spacer joining outrigger boom and float on a canoe
Name: yamwa
yaú, yaú-ri-, kka-yaú, ka-yaú-ú-
Comment: Cf. also PMc *ata-i- ‘to know’, PMc *kai2 ‘to inform’.

Description: platform on the outrigger booms of a canoe between the hull and the float
Name: ? yaú[ln]awa
yoko, yoko-fi
Comment: Cf. also PMc ? *Loo ‘be caught, overtaken, found’ posited by Goodenough (1995:76), with reflexes Pon lo ‘to be caught’, Kir oo-a ‘to overtake (someone)’, and Ksr lɔ ‘found, retrieved, recovered’.
